# Admin Dashboard Pattern

Admin pages show **internal metrics** that paying customers don't see: PMF scores, activation rates, system health, A/B test results, cohort analysis.

This rule documents the architecture for building admin-only views.

---

## Directory Structure

```
app/
  admin/
    growth/
      page.tsx         ← Growth metrics (PMF, activation, referrals)
    health/
      page.tsx         ← System health, uptime, error rates (future)
    cohorts/
      page.tsx         ← Retention curves by signup cohort (future)
```

**Rule:** All admin pages live under `app/admin/`. This makes authorization simple (one middleware rule).

---

## Authorization Pattern

### Role-Based Access (Admin-Only)

**API routes:**

```typescript
// app/api/pmf-survey/route.ts (GET endpoint)

export async function GET() {
  const session = await getServerSession(authOptions);
  if (!session?.user?.email) {
    return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Unauthorized' }, { status: 401 });
  }

  // Check role
  const user = await prisma.user.findUnique({
    where: { email: session.user.email },
    select: { role: true },
  });

  if (user?.role !== 'admin') {
    return NextResponse.json({ error: 'Unauthorized' }, { status: 403 });
  }

  // Return sensitive metrics
  const pmfScore = await calculatePmfScore();
  return NextResponse.json({ pmfScore });
}
```

**Page components:**

```typescript
// app/admin/growth/page.tsx

export default function GrowthMetricsPage() {
  const [metrics, setMetrics] = useState(null);
  const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    const fetchMetrics = async () => {
      const res = await fetchWithAuth('/api/pmf-survey');
      if (res.status === 403) {
        setError('Admin access required');
        return;
      }
      setMetrics(await res.json());
    };
    fetchMetrics();
  }, []);

  if (error) {
    return (
      <div className="text-center py-12 text-red-600">
        {error}
      </div>
    );
  }

  // Render admin view
}
```

**Why this pattern:**
- **Double-gated:** Session auth (logged in) + role check (is admin)
- API returns 403 (not 401) for insufficient permissions
- Client handles 403 gracefully (shows "access denied" instead of crashing)
- Role stored in database (easy to update, audit trail)

